just_use sidecar_audit.py

# label: TOOL
# role: drift detector — source files ↔ .claude sidecars

Two checks:

- **Coverage**: every non-test `*.go` / `*.py` / `*.elm` in the
  tree has a sibling `*.claude` sidecar. Missing sidecars are
  the single biggest silent-drift risk — new code accumulates
  without domain notes and the next session can't navigate it.
- **just_use target**: every sidecar's `just_use <file>` header
  points at an existing file in the same directory. Orphaned
  sidecars after renames / removals show up here.

Exits 0 clean, 1 on drift. Wired into `ops/check` as part of
the pre-commit preflight.

## Surface

- `python3 tools/sidecar_audit.py` — scan whole repo.

## Known exemptions

- Test runners (`test_*.py`, `*Test.elm`, `*_test.go`) — self-
  describing via file docstrings.
- Individual files listed in `EXEMPT_FILES` inside the script.
  Keep that list short; each entry should be justified by a
  comment next to it.

## Pointers

- Companion: `tools/apply_labels.py` (assigns labels to sidecars;
  doesn't check coverage).
- Semantic Go↔Elm drift is caught by the DSL conformance tests,
  not a name-set comparator. The old `parity_check.py` was
  retired 2026-04-20 because idiom differences (Elm
  encode/decoder + camelCase module-stripped names vs Go
  MarshalJSON + PascalCase) swamped any real signal.
